{"parse":{"title":"Ciacco","pageid":4228500,"revid":796078524,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><table class=\"plainlinks metadata ambox ambox-content ambox-Primary_sources\" role=\"presentation\"><tbody><tr><td class=\"mbox-image\"><div style=\"width:52px\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Question_book-new.svg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"Question book-new.svg\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/9/99/Question_book-new.svg/50px-Question_book-new.svg.png\" width=\"50\" height=\"39\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/9/99/Question_book-new.svg/75px-Question_book-new.svg.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/9/99/Question_book-new.svg/100px-Question_book-new.svg.png 2x\" data-file-width=\"512\" data-file-height=\"399\" /></a></div></td><td class=\"mbox-text\"><div class=\"mbox-text-span\">This article <b>relies too much on <a href=\"/wiki/Wikipedia:Verifiability\" title=\"Wikipedia:Verifiability\">references</a> to <a href=\"/wiki/Wikipedia:No_original_research#Primary,_secondary_and_tertiary_sources\" title=\"Wikipedia:No original research\">primary sources</a></b>.<span class=\"hide-when-compact\"> Please improve this  by adding <a href=\"/wiki/Wikipedia:No_original_research#Primary,_secondary_and_tertiary_sources\" title=\"Wikipedia:No original research\">secondary or tertiary sources</a>.</span>  <small><i>(September 2009)</i></small><small class=\"hide-when-compact\"><i> (<a href=\"/wiki/Help:Maintenance_template_removal\" title=\"Help:Maintenance template removal\">Learn how and when to remove this template message</a>)</i></small></div></td></tr></tbody></table>\n<div class=\"thumb tright\"><div class=\"thumbinner\" style=\"width:222px;\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Inferno_Canto_6_lines_49-52.jpg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/a1/Inferno_Canto_6_lines_49-52.jpg/220px-Inferno_Canto_6_lines_49-52.jpg\" width=\"220\" height=\"185\" class=\"thumbimage\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/a1/Inferno_Canto_6_lines_49-52.jpg/330px-Inferno_Canto_6_lines_49-52.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/a1/Inferno_Canto_6_lines_49-52.jpg/440px-Inferno_Canto_6_lines_49-52.jpg 2x\" data-file-width=\"987\" data-file-height=\"829\" /></a>  <div class=\"thumbcaption\"><div class=\"magnify\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Inferno_Canto_6_lines_49-52.jpg\" class=\"internal\" title=\"Enlarge\"></a></div>Dante meets Ciacco. Engraving by <a href=\"/wiki/Gustave_Dor%C3%A9\" title=\"Gustave Dor\u00e9\">Gustave Dor\u00e9</a></div></div></div>   \n<p><i><b>Ciacco</b></i> <small></small><span title=\"Representation in the International Phonetic Alphabet (IPA)\" class=\"IPA\"><a href=\"/wiki/Help:IPA/Italian\" title=\"Help:IPA/Italian\">[\u02c8t\u0283akko]</a></span> is one of the characters in the <i><a href=\"/wiki/Divine_Comedy\" title=\"Divine Comedy\">Divine Comedy</a></i> by <a href=\"/wiki/Dante_Alighieri\" title=\"Dante Alighieri\">Dante Alighieri</a> that were not yet well defined by historians. This is how he presents himself to Dante when he is in <a href=\"/wiki/Inferno_(Dante)\" title=\"Inferno (Dante)\">Hell</a>:\n</p>\n<blockquote><div class=\"poem\">\n<p>\u00abVoi cittadini mi chiamaste Ciacco;<br />\nper la dannosa colpa de la gola,<br />\ncome tu vedi, a la pioggia mi fiacco.\u00bb<br />\n<br />\n\u00abYe citizens were wont to call me Ciacco;<br />\nFor the pernicious sin of gluttony,<br />\nI, as thou seest, am battered by this rain.\u00bb<br />\n<br />\n<i>(Inferno, VI, 52-54)</i>\n</p>\n</div></blockquote>\n<p>This way introducing himself allows us to interpret it in various ways, but one of the oldest commentators of the Comedy suggests a derogatory nature of this name: \"Ciacco is said to be a pig's name, hence he was called this way for his gluttony.\"\n</p><p><a href=\"/wiki/Giovanni_Boccaccio\" title=\"Giovanni Boccaccio\">Giovanni Boccaccio</a> makes of Ciacco eighth story of the ninth day of the <i><a href=\"/wiki/Decameron\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Decameron\">Decameron</a></i>, describing him as \"the most gluttonous fellow that ever lived.\"<sup id=\"cite_ref-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup> However, the reference to Ciacco's name is somewhat ambiguous: he is referred to as the man \"whom everyone called Ciacco.\"<sup id=\"cite_ref-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup> It is hard to say if Boccaccio had sources for his writings aside from Dante, because this name has not been found in literature before Dante. According to Vittorio Sermonti, a scholar dedicated to the study of the Comedy, the hypothesis that this Ciacco is the poet Ciacco dell'Anguillara is not true<sup class=\"noprint Inline-Template Template-Fact\" style=\"white-space:nowrap;\">&#91;<i><a href=\"/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed\" title=\"Wikipedia:Citation needed\"><span title=\"This claim needs references to reliable sources. (August 2017)\">citation needed</span></a></i>&#93;</sup>.\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"References\">References</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Ciacco&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: References\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"reflist\" style=\"list-style-type: decimal;\">\n<div class=\"mw-references-wrap\"><ol class=\"references\">\n<li id=\"cite_note-1\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-1\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">558</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-2\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-2\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">558</span>\n</li>\n</ol></div></div>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"External_links\">External links</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Ciacco&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2\" title=\"Edit section: External links\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<ul><li><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://web.archive.org/web/20050912180255/http://www.stg.brown.edu/projects/decameron/engDecShowText.php?myID=nov0908&amp;expand=day09\">Novel VIII of the Ninth day of the Decameron</a></li></ul>\n<p>Boccaccio, Giovanni. Decameron. Trans. J. G. Nichols. New York: Everyman\u2019s Library/Alfred A. Knopf, 2009. Print.\n</p><p><br />\n</p>\n<table class=\"metadata plainlinks stub\" role=\"presentation\" style=\"background:transparent\"><tbody><tr><td><a href=\"/wiki/File:Litchar.png\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"Stub icon\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/ed/Litchar.png/30px-Litchar.png\" width=\"30\" height=\"30\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/ed/Litchar.png/45px-Litchar.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/ed/Litchar.png/60px-Litchar.png 2x\" data-file-width=\"128\" data-file-height=\"128\" /></a></td><td><i>This article about a <a href=\"/wiki/Literature\" title=\"Literature\">literature</a> character is a <a href=\"/wiki/Wikipedia:Stub\" title=\"Wikipedia:Stub\">stub</a>. You can help Wikipedia by <a class=\"external text\" href=\"//en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Ciacco&amp;action=edit\">expanding it</a>.</i><div class=\"plainlinks hlist navbar mini\" style=\"position: absolute; right: 15px; display: none;\"><ul><li class=\"nv-view\"><a href=\"/wiki/Template:Lit-char-stub\" title=\"Template:Lit-char-stub\"><abbr title=\"View this template\">v</abbr></a></li><li class=\"nv-talk\"><a href=\"/wiki/Template_talk:Lit-char-stub\" title=\"Template talk:Lit-char-stub\"><abbr title=\"Discuss this template\">t</abbr></a></li><li class=\"nv-edit\"><a class=\"external text\" href=\"//en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Template:Lit-char-stub&amp;action=edit\"><abbr title=\"Edit this template\">e</abbr